03988nam a22005535i 9780300161236DE-B159720200424112023.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200424t20102010ctu    fo  d z      eng d  a97803001612367 a10.12987/97803001612362doi  a(DE-B1597)485647  a(OCoLC)841171080  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  actucUS-CT 7aLAW0740002bisacsh04a346.04/82221 aPenalver, Eduardo M., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aProperty Outlaws :bHow Squatters, Pirates, and Protesters Improve the Law of Ownership /cSonia Katyal, Eduardo M. Penalver. 1aNew Haven, CT : bYale University Press, c[2010] 4cÂ©2010  a1 online resource (288 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tIntroduction -- tChapter 1. Why Property Outlaws? -- tChapter 2. Property And Intellectual Property -- tChapter 3. Acquisitive Outlaws: The Pioneers -- tChapter 4. Expressive Outlaws: Civil Rights Sit-Ins -- tChapter 5. Property Outlaws And Property Altlaws -- tChapter 6. Acquisitive Altlaws: The Treatment Action Campaign, Patents, And Public Health -- tChapter 7. Expressive Altlaws: Copyright And The New Liberation Of Information -- tChapter 8. Two Perspectives On Property Outlaws -- tChapter 9. Responding To Property Outlaws -- tChapter 10. The Informational Value Of Intellectual Property Disobedience -- tChapter 11. Responding To Acquisitive Altlaws -- tChapter 12. Responding To Expressive Altlaws -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aProperty Outlaws puts forth the intriguingly counterintuitive proposition that, in the case of both tangible and intellectual property law, disobedience can often lead to an improvement in legal regulation. The authors argue that in property law there is a tension between the competing demands of stability and dynamism, but its tendency is to become static and fall out of step with the needs of society. The authors employ wide-ranging examples of the behaviors of "property outlaws"-the trespasser, squatter, pirate, or file-sharer-to show how specific behaviors have induced legal innovation. They also delineate the similarities between the actions of property outlaws in the spheres of tangible and intellectual property. An important conclusion of the book is that a dynamic between the activities of "property outlaws" and legal innovation should be cultivated in order to maintain this avenue of legal reform.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aCivil disobedience. 0aIntellectual property. 0aRight of property. 0aRule of law. 7aLAW / Property.2bisacsh1 aKatyal, Sonia, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYUP eBook-Package 2000-2015z978311066772108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press eBook Package 2000-2013z978311053799440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300161236423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780300161236.jpg  a978-3-11-053799-4  Yale University Press eBook Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  a978-3-11-066772-1  YUP eBook-Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles